<article>
    <h1>Per&#xAD;sonal safety dur&#xAD;ing gar&#xAD;den&#xAD;ing</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200924/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-24"><time>2020-09-24</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | TELEVISION</span>
        - <span role="byline">By ARUL JOHN</span>
    </section>

    <p>Gar­den­ing can be a great way to en­joy the out­doors, get phys­i­cal ac­tiv­ity, beau­tify the com­mu­nity, and grow nu­tri­tious fruits and veg­eta­bles. Fol­low the tips be­low and you will be sure to en­joy many hours and days of safe, healthy and en­joy­able gar­den­ing.</p>
    <p>SAFETY FIRST</p>
    <p>Sharpen tools care­fully. Pow­ered and un­pow­ered tools and equip­ment can cause se­ri­ous in­jury.</p>
    <p>Fol­low in­struc­tions and warn­ing la­bels on chem­i­cals and lawn and gar­den equip­ment.</p>
    <p>Keep harm­ful chem­i­cals, tools, and equip­ment out of chil­dren’s reach.</p>
    <p>KNOW YOUR LIM­ITS</p>
    <p>Mon­i­tor your ac­tiv­i­ties and time in the sun to lower your risk for heat-re­lated ill­ness.</p>
    <p>Drink more flu­ids if you are out­side in hot weather for most of the day. Avoid drink­ing liq­uids that con­tain al­co­hol or large amounts of sugar, es­pe­cially in the heat.</p>

